<div class="header"><h1>How Glutamate Is Used</h1></div>
<div class="body">

<p>Glutamate is an amino acid that is found naturally in many foods, including
meat, dairy products, and vegetables. It is also produced by the body and plays
a crucial role in many functions, including:</p>

<ul>
<li>Neurotransmission: Glutamate is the primary excitatory neurotransmitter in the brain, meaning it helps transmit signals between nerve cells. It plays a key role in learning, memory, and other cognitive functions <sup><a href="#src-use-1">1</a>.</sup></li>

<li>Energy metabolism: Glutamate is used by the body to produce energy, particularly in the brain and muscles. It is also involved in the metabolism of other amino acids and the synthesis of proteins <sup><a href="#src-use-2">2</a>.</sup></li>

<li>Cell signaling: Glutamate can act as a signaling molecule and play a role in the regulation of various cellular processes, such as cell growth and differentiation <sup><a href="#src-use-3">3</a>.</sup></li>

<li>Metabolic functions: Glutamate is involved in the metabolism of nitrogen, which is necessary for the synthesis of various molecules, including proteins and nucleic acids.</li>
</ul>

<p>In summary, glutamate is an important amino acid that plays a vital role in many functions within the body. It is involved in neurotransmission, energy metabolism, cell signaling, and other metabolic processes.</p>

